"Abstract Intentionally or not, many businesses could be using second hand software. At one end of the spectrum, small businesses might pick up some cheap pcs from eBay, with a variety of already installed software. At the other end, software licences might be purchased (already installed on pcs or servers) as just part of a bigger asset purchase of another business. More recently we have seen the emergence of resellers such as discount-licensing.com, whose business model is to sell unwanted Microsoft application software (either from insolvent companies or from users with surplus licences). With the ever increasing cost of software there is, perhaps, a growing financial incentive to consider second hand software. However, the old adage, “caveat emptor” – let the buyer beware – remains as true today as it ever was, as there are a number of pitfalls to be wary of. In this article we look at some of the key practical and legal considerations to take into account when dealing with second hand software (and their related licences), particularly in the light of a couple of recent German cases concerning the resale of software."
